SIMPLE: clerical
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Clerical
<hw>Cler"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>clericalis</ets>. <ets>See</ets> <er>Clerk</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Of or pertaining to the clergy; suitable for the clergy.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>clerical</xex> education.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or relating to a clerk or copyist, or to
writing.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Clerical</xex> work.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>E.
Everett.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>characteristic of the work performed by a clerk,
secretary, or copyist, or suitable to be performed by a clerk.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Clerical</xex> staff.⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>A clerical error</b></col>, <cd>an error made in copying
or writing.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clericalism</ent>⟦br⟧
